, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bruer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: occupational name for a brewer, a dialect (Low German) form of   Brauer  .","Possibly an altered form of the cognate   Breuer  .","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm named Bruer, from the plural of <i>bru</i> ‘bridge’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brauer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Dieter, Erwin, Ewald, Gerhard, Benno, Claus, Elke, Gunther, Hans, Harro.","North German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (also <b>Bräuer</b>): occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle Low German <i>brūwer</i> or Middle High German <i>briuwer</i> ‘brewer’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"La","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Olaf  , also widely used in southwest Sweden."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummar